{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536453"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:07:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:07:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15800"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15800"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.07,0.11,0.68,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101104"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8491"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4359"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34670"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101104"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for her first pregnancy visit at eight weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A transvaginal ultrasound reveals a single gestational sac containing one placenta and one amniotic cavity. Two embryos are visualised with cardiac activity, but they appear to share body parts and cannot be separated from each other on different scanning planes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the embryological basis of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete splitting of a single embryonic disc before day 3","Division of a single embryo between days 4 and 8","Division of a single embryo between days 8 and 12","Incomplete splitting of a single embryonic disc after day 13","Fusion of two separate embryos during early development"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis ultrasound demonstrates conjoined twins, which develop when a single fertilised egg fails to completely separate during early embryonic development. The timing of the incomplete separation is crucial to understanding the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncomplete splitting of a single embryonic disc after day 13\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct embryological explanation for conjoined twins. By this stage, the embryonic disc has begun to differentiate, and incomplete separation results in shared body parts. The location and extent of sharing depends on which part of the embryonic disc fails to separate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFusion of two separate embryos\u003C/strong\u003E is a common misconception but is not the mechanism for conjoined twins. Each embryo develops within its own amniotic sac, making fusion physically impossible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete splitting before day 3\u003C/strong\u003E results in dichorionic diamniotic twins, each with their own placenta and amniotic sac. This early division allows each twin to develop its own chorion and amnion, leading to two separate placentas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDivision between days 4 and 8\u003C/strong\u003E results in monochorionic diamniotic twins - identical twins sharing a placenta but in separate amniotic sacs. This occurs when the inner cell mass of a single blastocyst splits during this timeframe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDivision between days 8 and 12\u003C/strong\u003E results in monochorionic monoamniotic twins, where twins share both the chorion and amniotic sac. This occurs after the formation of both the chorion and amnion, leading to a higher risk of complications such as cord entanglement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of conjoined twins can usually be made on ultrasound in the first trimester. Key sonographic features include a single gestational sac, shared body parts, and inability to separate the fetuses on different imaging planes. The prognosis depends on the site and extent of fusion, with some types being potentially separable after birth while others are incompatible with life. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Conjoined twins arise from incomplete separation of a single embryonic disc after day 13 of development","Early first trimester ultrasound is crucial for diagnosis of conjoined twins","The prognosis and management options for conjoined twins depend on the site and extent of fusion"],"references":["Kaufman, M.H. The embryology of conjoined twins. Childs Nerv Syst 20, 508\u2013525 (2004). https://doi.org/10.1007/s00381-004-0985-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83538"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15800"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83538"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-30T07:05:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-30T07:06:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8491"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101104"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","l